data.body:
Tom nkast jjag or whoever is working on this atm. 
Can we expose the getter on the two properties for texel width height in Texture2D.

internal float TexelWidth { get; private set; }
internal float TexelHeight { get; private set; }

to simply

public float TexelWidth { get; private set; }
public float TexelHeight { get; private set; }

This is extremely useful when exposed for all texture2d custom vertex uv element assignments, for calculating source rectangles image pixel coordinates to uv positions.

We already have Width Height exposed so a user could keep recalculating the reciprocal for each texture himself but... It would be nice however to expose the getter on this since its there already and only ever really needs to be calculated and set when it the texture itself is created or recreated. 
A public getter here is a mini feature.

_If this is a matter of hesitation on deciding on a final name just call it by its math proper name.
Or whatever id like to be able to use that though outside of a source build._ 

WidthReciprocal.
HeightReciprocal.


https://www.mathsisfun.com/reciprocal.html

> _Though the result is essentially used as a coefficient. 
> Your getting a reciprocal so i guess that is clearer besides that's what the descriptions for.
> e.g. 
> ///
> /// Returns the textures width reciprocal. 
> /// This value is commonly used as a coefficient against image texel positions to find uv coordinates
> ///_
> 

Btw the other associated classes to spritebatch look a lot lot better. 
Though spritebatch is really fat now lol.

**One more thing.**

I was wondering if we could get a set of vectors in the glyph class that directly relates to the uv bounds of each glyph. 
A) Since each spritefont builds its glyphs based on a single texture. 
B) Since each texture has but one texel coefficient which is created with the loaded spritefont. 
C) Then each glyph should directly have its source uv vectors stored per glyph. 
Besides the bounds, those constructed uv vectors can be directly placed into the vertex uv's, LT LB RT RB. 
There really is no point in calculating them from the glyph bounds at all in the draw, even with a single multiply.
Because we look up the glyph per character anyways, and those char source uv's like and which are created from the char source bounds, will never change after being loaded for each font. 
To say they are per font per char constructs and are not dynamic.

```
public struct Glyph
    {
        /// <summary>
        /// The char associated with this glyph.
        /// </summary>
        public char Character;
        /// <summary>
        /// Rectangle in the font texture where this letter exists.
        /// </summary>
        public Rectangle BoundsInTexture;

        // The uv bounds of this glyph in the texture
        // e.g when glyph is created LT = new Vector2( BoundsInTexture.X * texture.TexelWidth, ... )

        public Vector2 LT;  
        public Vector2 LB;
        public Vector2 RT;
        public Vector2 RB;

        .... ect....

       // The below in drawstring then gets shorted to a lookup for a already looked up glyph.

	public void DrawString ( 
        ....

       _texCoordTL.X = currentGlyph.BoundsInTexture.X * spriteFont.Texture.TexelWidth;
       _texCoordTL.Y = currentGlyph.BoundsInTexture.Y * spriteFont.Texture.TexelHeight;
       _texCoordBR.X = (currentGlyph.BoundsInTexture.X + currentGlyph.BoundsInTexture.Width) * spriteFont.Texture.TexelWidth;
       _texCoordBR.Y = (currentGlyph.BoundsInTexture.Y + currentGlyph.BoundsInTexture.Height) * spriteFont.Texture.TexelHeight;

      // to
      _texCoordTL = currentGlyph.LT;
      _texCoordBR = currentGlyph.RB; 

```
